readme.md
    20→## Benefits over plain `fetch`
    22→- Simpler API
    23→- Method shortcuts (`ky.post()`)
    24→- Treats non-2xx status codes as errors (after redirects)
    25→- Retries failed requests
    26→- JSON option
    27→- Timeout support
    28→- URL prefix option
    29→- Instances with custom defaults
    30→- Hooks
    31→- TypeScript niceties (e.g. `.json()` supports generics and defaults to `unknown`, not `any`)
    32→
    33→## Install
    35→```sh
    36→npm install ky
    37→```
    38→
    39→###### CDN
    41→- [jsdelivr](https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/ky/+esm)
    42→- [unpkg](https://unpkg.com/ky)
    43→- [esm.sh](https://esm.sh/ky)
      →…
    45→## Usage
    47→```js
    48→import ky from 'ky';
    49→
    50→const json = await ky.post('https://example.com', {json: {foo: true}}).json();
    51→
    52→console.log(json);
    53→//=> {data: '🦄'}
    54→```
    55→
    56→With plain `fetch`, it would be:
    57→
    58→```js
    59→class HTTPError extends Error {}
    60→
    61→const response = await fetch('https://example.com', {
    62→	method: 'POST',
    63→	body: JSON.stringify({foo: true}),
    64→	headers: {
    65→		'content-type': 'application/json'
    66→	}
    67→});
    68→
    69→if (!response.ok) {
    70→	throw new HTTPError(`Fetch error: ${response.statusText}`);
    71→}
    72→
    73→const json = await response.json();
    74→
    75→console.log(json);
    76→//=> {data: '🦄'}
    77→```
    78→
    79→If you are using [Deno](https://github.com/denoland/deno), import Ky from a URL. For example, using a CDN:
    80→
    81→```js
    82→import ky from 'https://esm.sh/ky';
    83→```
    84→
    85→## API
    87→### ky(input, options?)
    89→The `input` and `options` are the same as [`fetch`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/WindowOrWorkerGlobalScope/fetch), with additional `options` available (see below).
    90→
    91→Returns a [`Response` object](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Response) with [`Body` methods](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Fetch_API/Using_Fetch#body) added for convenience. So you can, for example, call `ky.get(input).json()` directly without having to await the `Response` first. When called like that, an appropriate `Accept` header will be set depending on the body method used. Unlike the `Body` methods of `window.Fetch`, these will throw an `HTTPError` if the response status is not in the range of `200...299`. Also, `.json()` will return an empty string if body is empty or the response status is `204` instead of throwing a parse error due to an empty body.
    92→
    93→Available body shortcuts: `.json()`, `.text()`, `.formData()`, `.arrayBuffer()`, `.blob()`, and `.bytes()`. The `.bytes()` shortcut is only present when the runtime supports `Response.prototype.bytes()`.
    94→
    95→```js
    96→import ky from 'ky';
    97→
    98→const user = await ky('/api/user').json();
    99→
   100→console.log(user);
   101→```
   102→
   103→⌨️ **TypeScript:** Accepts an optional [type parameter](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/2/generics.html), which defaults to [`unknown`](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/2/functions.html#unknown), and is passed through to the return type of `.json()`.
   104→
   105→```ts
   106→import ky from 'ky';
   107→
   108→// user1 is unknown
   109→const user1 = await ky('/api/users/1').json();
   110→// user2 is a User
   111→const user2 = await ky<User>('/api/users/2').json();
   112→// user3 is a User
   113→const user3 = await ky('/api/users/3').json<User>();
   114→
   115→console.log([user1, user2, user3]);
   116→
   117→// Get raw bytes (when supported by the runtime)
   118→const bytes = await ky('/api/file').bytes();
   119→console.log(bytes instanceof Uint8Array);
   120→```
   121→
